content:
Friendly thought to those getting the new covid vaccine and flu vaccines.

I mean this with as much kindness as I can muster‚Ä¶ please hear me:

How you feel for a few days is how many of us with Long Covid have felt for *years*. It‚Äôs unrelenting, debilitating, life stealing.

Please be mindful when you post. I‚Äôve been negatively triggered by some people catastrophizing feeling sick for a few days. Please, I beg you, don‚Äôt do this.

#Covid #LongCovid

content:
For a lot of binders, one of the preferred adhesives makes use of methyl cellulose (MC) instead of wheat paste since MC doesn't get moldy as easily as wheat paste. I don't have ready access to MC locally. But I did find sodium carboxymethyl cellulose (sod. CMC). I wondered if I could use sod CMC instead of MC. Turns out that sod CMC may have better grip than MC. Ordered 500g of technical grade sod CMC. Can't wait to try it out.

#bookbinding #makers #hobby

content: It's going to be really interesting over the next few years to see how gravel racing takes off as more and more world tour roadies graduate to gravel, a space where older bodies with better endurance but slightly diminished top end power can excel. It's so interesting that cycling works like this, rather than just having older categories for 'normal' races. I imagine it will become a bit of a rite of passage to graduate to the longer, tougher rides at the end of a world tour career #cycling

content:
Happy #InternationalSawfishDay! Here is a #sawfish in the earliest surviving version of Zakariya al-Qazwini's 'Aja'ib al-Makhluqat wa Ghara'ib al-Mawjudat (aka The Wonders of Creation), from Wasit, Iraq, 1280 CE.
(LOC)
The Wonders of Creation is a famous work of Islamic cosmography probably first made c.1260s CE, and for centuries after was reproduced across the Islamic world. In later versions the sawfish is often more like a swordfish, as seen in the 2nd image from a 15th c. CE text.
(NMAA)
